<a href="javascript:card_browser(312)">Cave Troll of Moria, Scourge of the Black Pit</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(125)">Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(47)">Uruk Savage</a> x2<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x4<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(64)">Fool of a Took!</a> x2<br>
<br>
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>ies x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(90)">Relics of Moria</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(884)">Saruman&#39;s Snows</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(36)">Spies of Saruman</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x3    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> First off, my relationship with the Snowbomb. Back in those goold old days, I designed a Snowbomb as the tournament deck for my friend, and through endless hours of testing, we perfected it to the absolute best deck out there. It played 100 games, and won 100 games (okay, exaggeration), against every deck we pitted it against, as we tailored it to be able to counter every Free People&#39;s strategy, every commonly-used Free People&#39;s card out there. Every counter had our own counter. We bordered on cheating, and therefore of course good times did not last. (oh well, we never got past Change of Plans though, but give me a shout if somebody plays Change of Plans in your parts)<br>
<br>
It went 12-1 in tournament play, losing only to a freak loss to Return to Its Master. Then of course, you know the script. Rule of 4 came down and worst off was the accompanying erratas.<br>
<br>
I put up here a scaffolding of a new Snowbomb. Of course, we&#39;ll have to examine the problems brought about by the erratas.<br>
<br>
(2) Gimli, Dwarf of Erebor<br>
Dwarf Companion<br>
If the twilight pool has fewer than 2 tokens, exert Gimli and add 2 twilight to put a card from hand beneath your draw deck.<br>
<br>
Of course, before, we could stick every Tom, pipeweed, Harry we wanted (aka Runner, Sneak, Scout) underneath our deck. Now, it is much more limited, yet still workable. For the twilight requirement, we will use Bilbo + Consorting with Sting (if opponent plays Orcs) to be able to use the ability multiple times in a single turn. and for the exertion requirement, healing with Elrond + vitality-adders like Endurance of Dwarves will be used.<br>
<br>
Of course, Goblin Sneaks can complement the ability. The need to recycle Goblin Sneaks is much more important this time.<br>
<br>
Rule of Four<br>
During the Fellowship Phase, the Free Peoples Player may not draw or take into hand more than 4 cards.<br>
<br>
Of course, the only cards that get around it now are currently Gandalf, the Grey Pilgrim and Book of Mazarbul. Obviously, for drawing power, we will use the latter. You can put out a maximum of 6 Dwarves in this deck (though watch out for Enquea, the drawing power does not justify a dead Gimli if you haven&#39;t finished the underneath-stacking) without violating the Rule. Delving provided for some additional &#39;real&#39; drawing. Book with 4-5 Dwarves (a more realistic number) and a Delving in a single turn nets you around 16 cards for that Free Peoples turn. Not only does it allow you to get to the bottom faster and get the cards required, it also provides additional protection and wealthy shadow options.<br>
<br>
---------------------------<br>
<br>
For those of you not in the know, the Snowbomb, coined by Alex Tennet on this site, works by using Gimli and Goblin Sneaks to set up the bottom of your draw deck, while using drawing power to get to the bottom quicker, and saving cards required in hand or beneath the draw deck when they do not interfere with the combo. Then when the time is ripe and the bomb is ready to explode, you use Fool of a Took! to draw into all the Moria Orcs at the bottom of your deck. And as your opponent smiles, you slap down Uruk Savage + Snows + Spies to remove all external interference from other companions to bring onto Frodo the inevitable death.<br>
<br>
Some foreseeable problems you might see in the paragraph alone.<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent does not play Hobbits for Fool of a Took</b> - This is an annoyance, not a game-breaker. Fellowships without Hobbits, not even an ally, tend to be small, and thus, Scavengers/Relics + a total shadow hand can still get out a respectable force of above 10 Orcs. It is also rare nowadays to see a deck without Filibert or Sam, at least.<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent uses Secret Sentinels/Albert Dreary/Vilya to get rid of Spies + Snows</b> - That&#39;s why you run Anduin Confluence instead of Anduin Wilderland. Wait for them to trip the site before you unleash the bomb. In fact, if you set it up too early (Site 5?), it is possible to just hold your shadow cards in hand and keep passing on all your phases until the time is ripe after the Mirror errata. Also, with the errata on Thror&#39;s Map and the relative anonymity of Pathfinder, he will trip Confluence, unlike last time where we had to apply anti-Thror&#39;s Map tech. For those with Pathfinder, it will take them some losses for them to start using the card on Site 7. As for Hobbit decks which do use Thror&#39;s Map? They don&#39;t have any of the maneuver anti-condition cards. Let them have their site.<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent has toooooo many companions</b> - Usually 10-15 Orcs out can kill any Fellowship but occasionally, you do meet the FREAK deck that runs 9 companions, Aragorn RotN, Sam, PP and Boromir + Saga with Horn of Boromir. The old Bomb was more efficient in dealing with this with stuff like Goblin Warrior and 2 Enquea.<br>
<br>
<b>Gandalf Sleeps me just as I plan to loose my swarm</b> - Again, more of an annoyance than hindrance. Between Runners and Scouts, you should leave more than enough for Savage + Snows + Spies<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent stays behind me</b> - If you bid 0 and always plan to go 2nd, shouldn&#39;t be a problem. Also, everybody keeps double-moving when they utterly destroy your 5-strength Orcs.<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent plays discard</b> - These decks were already rare. With the Mirror errata, you are almost absolutely safe. If your opponent does play a few Orc Inquisitors, Gimli actually offers some discard protection of your important cards. And no, as much as double-Desperate Measures as your are down to the 10 Orcs at the bottom of your deck sounds way too scary, yes, it is too scary to happen in real life.<br>
<br>
<b>My Opponent uses archery/Trust Me/PATHS</b> - You obviously haven&#39;t been paying attention. Spies cancels archery. Snows cancels Trust Me and PATHS. Anduin Confluence cancels the allies who might cancel your Spies and Snows. Inadequate site control in the game currently (read above) means your Anduin Confluence will not be cancelled.<br>
<br>
--------------------<br>
<br>
I can talk a whole day about how to play this deck, but it is more of an experential deck, in that you will need to play it a few times to understand it, and to wield it like a weapon. Keep in mind that the deck-list is just a preliminary version. It does have certain flaws. For example, the Free Peoples is very flawed currently, will not fare well against Nazgul and only a little better against Uruks.<br>
<br>
Basically, all your Fellowship has to do is the DSS formula. Draw, stack, survive. You bid 0, giving your opponent no advantage. All you do is to survive. Always move 1 site a turn. NEVER 2 sites a turn. Though ocassionally, if you have the chance to start the game and are not playing against a newbie (newbies tend to always single-move), you can start the Hobbiton Party Field to get the engine running.<br>
<br>
My ratio of the cards needed to set up the combo should be adequate. Usually okay, and sometimes a bad draw. Whatever, just stack as many Orcs at the bottom as possible in your position (watch out for Sauron Orcs who can destroy you if you exerted Gimli once too many). There preferably should be a Sneak and Scavengers in the stack in case of emergencies (the Sneak/Scimitar combo), plus lots of Runners and Scouts. You can also stack Uruk Savage/Saruman&#39;s Snows/Spies at the bottom if they will not interfere too much with Fool of a Took or for discard protection.<br>
<br>
For your Fellowship, remember, you just want to survive, so take it slowly and take calculated risks. If you can evade Enquea or survive against Savagery, drop more Dwarves to fuel Book of Mazarbul. Gimli CANNOT die unless you already have a healthy stack waiting at the bottom of your deck.<br>
<br>
Bilbo + Party Guests with Consorting and Sting usually means 4+ twilight gone a turn which allows you to use Gimli, vitality permitting, to stack 3+ (speaking of which, remember to only put Endurance on Gimli). Aragorn is simply fodder in the greatest emergency, and for you to take advantage of The Prancing Pony. Realm of Dwarrowdelf? If everything screwed up for you and you have a thick draw deck left and your opponent is speeding, but a sizable stack underneath and the cards required in your hand, throw all caution away and DUMP your draw deck to reveal the gems underneath. With, say, 4 Dwarves out, and you pumping each Dwarf +3 with 9 cards, that&#39;s 36 cards gone from your draw deck.<br>
<br>
As for shadow, Goblin Sneak is pivotal. Ensure you have at least 1 Sneak, 1 Scavenger and lots of Runners and Scouts at the bottom of your draw deck. Cave Troll is put for a measure of stopping power to ensure your opponent doesn&#39;t try some cheeky quadruple-move without getting scatched. Also, he works with Fool of a Took so you can stack him underneath to get round a trickier Fellowship. Goblin Warrior might be a good addition to get rid of Thrarin and Greatest Kingdom if you meet one (destroys this deck), though I don&#39;t have the space, but this deck does have some room for expansion of deck-size (usually deck out in 5,6,7).<br>
<br>
Why no Balrog? Simply because you play him from your draw deck. Yay. and you SHUFFLE YOUR DRAW DECK. &#39;nuff said. Why no Swarms? This deck&#39;s &#39;hand-extension&#39; mechanism, a vital strategy in swarming decks, is not Swarms. It is the bottom of your draw deck. And if you think your 5-7 strength Orcs are ever going to survive the archery phase AND win skirmishes, think again.<br>
<br>
--------------------<br>
<br>
As said before, this is a preliminary version that requires much tweaking before it can become the unstoppable force it once was. I am working. In the meantime, I urge you to D-mail or e-mail me with comments or questions before you go and give your 1-star. Some of the intricacies in this deck are not plainly discernible in a quick glance, and do require further explanation, and I do not have the patience to type out a thesis paper in this space. And don&#39;t be surprised if the deck looks rather scrappy. The old Snowbomb looked rather unworkable, but it worked, and produced excellent results.<br>
<br>
I also do have a deck-list of my friend&#39;s old Snowbomb if you&#39;re interested. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=25753"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=25753" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
